events.description:

events.name: Cloud Study Jam : IoT in the Google Cloud
events.description:
Want to use the Google Cloud platform for your IoT project, but don't know where to begin? Join us for our Cloud Study Jam: IoT in the Google Cloud!

Get official Google training, a $55+ value, free of charge. Together we'll work through several IoT Google Cloud labs. You will get hands-on experience with the IoT on Cloud.

Then after our live session, you will have free access to more labs you can finish at home. Complete all labs in the quest and earn a Google-hosted badge for your online profile, and additional 30 days access to the training platform to compete any labs you want

Bring a laptop and charger (PC, Mac or Chromebook)! The labs will run on all of the latest versions of the popular browsers. For the best experience, make sure your laptop has Firefox or Chrome installed. Don’t forget your charger.

Location: TBA

Agenda:
7:00pm: Internet of Things: Qwik Start
7:45pm: Break
8:00pm: Streaming IoT Data to Google Cloud Storage
9:00pm: Event ends

events.name: Using Firebase and JAMstack to  create a completely* free web presence.

venue.name: Bank of Ireland Workbench
venue.address_1: St Patrick's St St Patrick's St

events.description:
This talk is an overview of the Google Firebase platform and how to set up a project on it. This project will be a website for a small business and the demo will show how to use completely free resources to create a credible web presence. There will also be an introduction to static site generators and the JAMstack and how these fit neatly into the Firebase way of doing things.

The demo will include:
Using Firebase Hosting to host a .com domain with a https certificate.
Using Firebase Database to create a simple API
Using Firebase Authentication to create a password-protected section of the website
Web frontend techniques (Vue, Bootstrap)
Static site generators and markdown

*completely - everything except .com domain registration.

Speaker: Aidan Kileen
He is a full-stack web developer and technical trainer working for Professional Training in Cork. He wrote his first web application in 1997, while working for Compuserve and has worked with most web technologies as they have evolved since. He teaches full-stack web development (MySQL administration and tuning, Node.js, Java & the Spring framework, front end web development, advanced CSS, JavaScript, Angular & Vue) for Professional Training and software development consultancy.

events.name: DevFest Cork 2019
events.description:
GDG Cork announces their first-ever DevFest.

Following are the amazing group speakers and their talks :

> Solving the World's Problems with Machine Learning: Toju Duke (Regional Product Lead)

Identifying the world's top problems, analyzing creative innovations of applied machine learning, and suggesting best practices for intuitive machine learning Eg Problem framing, expectation setting, building your first model, etc.

> GraphQL - a technology to watch: Aidan Killeen (Techincal Trainer)

This talk will introduce GraphQL and cover the pros and cons, particularly with respect to the more traditional RESTful web services that have become the mainstay of web backends. It will demonstrate some of the key features and how they can improve the lives of developers and other users of the service. It will also cover the main frameworks for creating a GraphQL service in node.js, Java and .NET.

> Analyzing and querying large datasets using Bigquery: Johannes Ahlmann (CEO Sensatus Ltd.)

Google Bigquery is a great offering both for datasets already hosted on BigQuery as well for your own large datasets that you wish to query quickly. I will give examples of existing datasets such as GitHub archive, Reddit posts, libraries.io, gdelt.org as well as using BigQuery for queries on a large private dataset.

> Getting started with microcontrollers and Google Cloud IoT Core: Gautier Mecling (Google Developer Expert)

In this talk, we will start with a famous and affordable microcontroller unit. We will first discover how to write code for this MCU so we can get environment data. Then we will connect the microcontroller to the Cloud using Google Cloud IoT Core. Our goal is to discover what these online Cloud IoT solutions offer, and why you may (or may not) need those.

> Understanding Principle Component Analysis: Urja Pawar (PhD in Collaboration with MckessonStudent )

The talk will start with why we use PCA in the data pre-processing and how it actually works. It will briefly cover methods to achieve PCA and existing libraries and list some scenarios when PCA can be helpful. In the end, there will be a small demo that can be practised by participants then and there to visualize how PCA works.
